ks to see how they are run.  I will grant you, all tracks have their problems, but you can bet that when a fight or something does break out is the exception rather than the norm.  At Isom, you can generally lay your money down that you will get to see a fight before the night is over.  To address the comment that he is not in it for the money, why else has he opened a track?  It was not for the love of the sport I can promise you that.  How does a man that had never been to a go kart race prior to opening his track have such a general love for the sport and the competition as a whole if he doesn't put forth any effort to promote the track?  He doesn't want any outsiders to come in first of all because he says they always win all the money.  Well, if you don't open your track to everyone you're only limiting the competition and hurting your racers.  No one benefits from that.  You only learn by going up against the best, not by running the same four karts every weekend.  What are you learning if you run the same classes against the same karts at the same track weekend after weekend?  What kind of victory is that?   Also, the money races he does have are not guaranteed.  This is really hurting the reputation of the track and the management.  It is the racers responsibility to pay the purses at Isom, not the track as it is anywhere else.  I for one would rather go to a race where the track cares enough about the racers to pay the purse than to cut it when he thinks he might not clear enough money that night.  Kart racing is not about money and the management at Isom have a lot to learn about the sport in general if it is going to remain open.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> Branch</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#FF9300>(3/10/04 3:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fkartanddriverfrm21.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicI